# Huzlly — Custom Tiptap Bubble Menu inside Repeating Group

## Problem this solves
The "Rich text editor (Tiptap.dev)" plugin's built-in Bubble Menu feature works by
taking an **ID Attribute** you set on a menu element, then internally doing something
equivalent to `document.getElementById(id)` to find and position that menu.

Inside a **Repeating Group**, Bubble does not guarantee a unique ID per row for elements
whose ID Attribute is a static string — every row can end up trying to reference the
same ID, and `getElementById()` only ever returns the first match in the document.
Result: the plugin's native bubble menu only works correctly for the first row.

This script bypasses the plugin's built-in mechanism entirely. It talks directly to the
raw Tiptap `Editor` instance of each row and shows/hides/positions your **own custom
menu element** based on the real text selection in that row — so it works correctly
for every row in the Repeating Group, not just the first one.

**Important:** This script does NOT apply any formatting itself (no Bold/Italic/Heading
commands are run from this code). Formatting is applied entirely by your existing
Bubble workflows attached to each menu button. This script's only job is:
show the menu, hide the menu, and position the menu correctly.

---

## How it finds the editor instance for each row

Each Tiptap input in your Repeating Group renders (approximately) like this:

```
<div id="tiptap-proposal-0">              <-- your Bubble "ID Attribute", one per row
  <div id="tiptapEditor-xxxxxxxxx">       <-- auto-generated by Bubble/plugin
    <div class="ProseMirror" ...>         <-- the actual editable area
      ...content...
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
```

The real Tiptap `Editor` object (the one with `.chain()`, `.state`, `.on()`, etc.) is
attached directly on the `.ProseMirror` DOM node as a property: `proseMirrorEl.editor`.
This was confirmed by inspecting `Object.keys()` of that element in DevTools — it
showed `['pmViewDesc', 'editor']`.

So the discovery chain is:

```
wrapper (your ID Attribute)
  → find child whose id starts with "tiptapEditor-"
    → find its child with class "ProseMirror"
      → .editor  ← this is the real Tiptap Editor instance
```

This logic lives in `getEditorFromWrapper()`.

---

## How row index is tracked

Your wrapper IDs follow the pattern `tiptap-proposal-{Current cell's index}`, so
`0`, `1`, `2`... The script extracts this index from the wrapper's ID and uses it as
a key to:
- cache the editor instance (`editorsByIndex`)
- find the matching menu element for that row (`bubble-menu-tiptap-proposal-{index}`)
- find the matching bounds group for that row (used for positioning, see below)

This is why `WRAPPER_ID_PREFIX` and `MENU_ID_PREFIX` must use the **same index
numbering** — the script assumes row `N`'s menu has the same `{index}` suffix as row
`N`'s wrapper.

**Note on row re-render:** listener attachment is tracked by *editor identity*
(`attachedEditorByIndex`), not just by index. If Bubble ever destroys and re-renders a
row at the same index (re-sort, filter refresh, data refresh), a brand-new Tiptap
`Editor` instance appears at that index. Tracking by index alone would see "already
attached for index 3" and skip re-attaching listeners to the new instance — silently
breaking that row's menu until a full page reload. Comparing `attachedEditorByIndex[index] !== editor` catches this and re-attaches whenever the instance actually changes.

---

## Why Repeating Groups need re-scanning (MutationObserver)

Rows in a Repeating Group can load asynchronously, get added, or get re-rendered by
Bubble as data changes. A single one-time scan on page load would miss rows that
aren't in the DOM yet.

`tryAttachAll()` scans for all current wrapper elements and attaches listeners to any
row it hasn't already attached to. A `MutationObserver` on `document.body` re-runs this
scan every time the DOM changes anywhere on the page, so newly-rendered rows get picked
up automatically. Two extra `setTimeout` safety-net scans (1s and 3s after load) cover
any edge-case timing where the observer might miss something during initial page load.

